On 12 July 1213, [[Frederick II, Holy Roman Emperor]] made a [[Golden Bull]] by which Frederick offered his obedience to the [[Pope]] and pledged himself to the principle of free canonical elections by the chapters, unhampered liberty of appeal to Rome on ecclesiastical issues, and abandonment of the traditional rights of the Crown to the personal estate of deceased bishops (''Spolienrecht'') and the Revenues of vacant sees (''Regalienrecht'').<ref>Leeper 1941 pp. 297</ref>
