{{short description|Middle East and North Africa region}}
{{About|the geographic region||Mena (disambiguation)}}
{{Redirect|WANA||Wana (disambiguation)}}
{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}
'''MENA''' is an [[English language|English-language]] [[acronym]] referring to the '''[[Middle East]] and [[North Africa]]''' region. An alternative for the same group of countries is '''WANA''' ([[West Asia]] and North Africa). The term covers an extensive region stretching from [[Morocco]] to [[Iran]], including all [[Mashriq]] and [[Maghreb]] countries. This toponym is roughly synonymous with the term the [[Greater Middle East]].

The population of the MENA region at its least extent is estimated to be around 381 million people. This constitutes about 6% of the total world population. The MENA acronym is often used in [[Education in the Middle East and North Africa|academia]], military planning, disaster relief, media planning as a broadcast region, and business writing.<ref name="worldbank">{{cite web|url=http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/MENAEXT/0,,menuPK:247619~pagePK:146748~piPK:146812~theSitePK:256299,00.html|title=World Bank Definition: MENA|publisher=Worldbank.org|accessdate=28 November 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029180410/http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/MENAEXT/0,,menuPK:247619~pagePK:146748~piPK:146812~theSitePK:256299,00.html|archivedate=29 October 2014|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weforum.org/en/events/WorldEconomicForumontheMiddleEastandNorthAfrica/index.htm|title=World Economic Forum on the Middle East and North Africa, Marrakech, Morocco, 26-28 October 2010|work=World Economic Forum on the Middle East and North Africa 2010 - World Economic Forum|accessdate=28 November 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66ooOPiYU?url=http://www.weforum.org/events/world-economic-forum-middle-east-and-north-africa-2010|archivedate=10 April 2012|df=}}</ref>

==Controversy==
Due to the geographic ambiguity and [[Eurocentrism|Eurocentric]] nature of the term "Middle East", some people prefer use of the terms '''Arab World''', '''WANA''' ([[West Asia]] and North Africa)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/html/cgiar/newsletter/april97/8beltagy.html|title=West Asia and North Africa: A Regional Vision|publisher=Worldbank.org|accessdate=28 November 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027183217/http://www.worldbank.org/html/cgiar/newsletter/april97/8beltagy.html|archivedate=27 October 2014|df=}}</ref> or the less common '''NAWA''' (North Africa-West Asia).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agu.org/pubs/crossref/2003/2003GL017862.shtml|title=Welcome|publisher=Agu.org|accessdate=28 November 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050430023759/http://www.agu.org/pubs/crossref/2003/2003GL017862.shtml|archivedate=30 April 2005|df=}}</ref> Both the [[Arab world]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Malone|first=David|date=25 October 2003|accessdate=3 January 2011|newspaper=[[World Bank]]|location=Washington D.C.|url=http://data.worldbank.org/region/arab-world|title=Arab World Data|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713110839/http://data.worldbank.org/region/arab-world|archivedate=13 July 2016|df=}}</ref> and MENA region remain the most common terms and are used by most organizations, academia, and political entities flexibly, including those in the region itself. The [[World Bank]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/events/2016/10/20/financial-education-in-the-arab-world|title=Financial education in the Arab World: Strategies, Implementation and Impact|work=World Bank|accessdate=2016-10-20|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104141241/http://www.worldbank.org/en/events/2016/10/20/financial-education-in-the-arab-world|archivedate=2016-11-04|df=}}</ref> [[UNDP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabstates.undp.org/|title=United Nations Development Programme in the Arab States|work=UNDP|accessdate=2016-11-03|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119093407/http://www.arabstates.undp.org/|archivedate=2016-11-19|df=}}</ref> and even the [[UNSC]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Malone|first=David|date=25 October 2003|accessdate=3 January 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]|location=Beirut|url=http://www.worldpress.org/Mideast/1694.cfm|title=Reforming the Security Council: Where Are the Arabs?|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101124223008/http://worldpress.org/Mideast/1694.cfm|archivedate=24 November 2010|df=}}</ref> all use both terms.

