{{Use British English|date=October 2017}}
{{Italic title}}
'''''The Complaint of the Black Knight''''', by the [[England|English]] monk [[John Lydgate]], is the oldest surviving book printed in [[Scotland]], which displays the printing date: 4 April 1508<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.500yearsofprinting.org/|title=Printing is one of Scotland's oldest surviving industries|publisher=500 Years of Printing in Scotland|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref> (see [[1508 in poetry]]). In 2010 it was chosen by [[UNESCO]] to become part of its [[Memory of the World Register]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.scotsman.com/news/World-won39t-forget-Scotland39s-rich.6417811.jp|title=World won't forget Scotland's rich past|date=14 July 2010|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=14 July 2010|location=Edinburgh|first=ShãN|last=Ross}}</ref>

Printed in [[Edinburgh]] by [[Chepman and Myllar Press|Chepman and Myllar]], the book was often falsely attributed in Scotland as a work of [[Geoffrey Chaucer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nls.uk/printing/title.cfm?id=74457612|title=The Chepman and Myllar prints|publisher=National Library of Scotland|accessdate=14 July 2010}}</ref>

